<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-355-582  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 355 582.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  April 5 1990 n1208 p10(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Heads together for a box with brains. (Japan's Ministry ofInternational Trade and Industry plans 10-year neural networkproject)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Cross, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Japan's Ministry of Trade and Information (MITI) plans a 10-yearresearch program to develop the technology that will make neuralnetwork computers a viable reality.andP;  The goal of the technology isto emulate the human brain's ability to learn, act on experienceand resolve ill-defined or 'fuzzy' problems.andP;  The MITI effort willbegin in April, 1990, but the agency hopes such conferences as therecent one in Tokyo organized by the Japan Information ProcessingDevelopment Center will help develop the research program.andP;  All ofJapan's major computer makers are expected to be involved in theprogram, and several are already investigating the technology.andO;Toshiba is developing a neural word processor, Fujitsu hasdemonstrated simulated neural networks and NEC demonstrated asystem that helps arrange songs.andP;  The MITI program will focus ondeveloping electronic devices that will be composed of neuralnetworks.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Neural NetworksResearch and DevelopmentGoals and ObjectivesProduct DevelopmentComputer IndustryManufacturersJapan. Ministry of International Trade and Industry.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>